    "date": "2026-04-15",
    "tags": ["Meta Muse Spark", "AI vs human scientists", "VC funding record", "humanoid robots", "China robotics"],
    "fresh": true,
    "content": "**AI & Robotics Snacks** — April 15, 2026\n\n---\n\n## 🧬 Meta Releases Its First AI Model Since Spending $14B to Hire Alexandr Wang\n\nAfter nine months and $14 billion in hiring, Meta Superintelligence Labs has produced Muse Spark — its first significant model release from the new division.\n\n- **What it is:** A model from Meta's newly formed Superintelligence Labs, led by Scale AI founder Alexandr Wang. Meta is positioning this as its answer to GPT-4o and Gemini.\n- **The context:** Meta spent 14 billion dollars and nine months to enter a race OpenAI and Google have been running for two years. The strategy is \"move fast and acquire someone else's talent.\"\n\n*Nine months, $14 billion, and a model called Muse Spark. The hype team is working overtime.*\n\n**Sources:** [CNBC](https://www.cnbc.com/2026/04/08/meta-debuts-first-major-ai-model-since-14-billion-deal-to-bring-in-alexandr-wang.html)\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Nature Study: Human Scientists Still Beat AI Agents at Doing Science\n\nA peer-reviewed study in Nature found that human researchers outperform the best available AI agent systems on complex scientific tasks — meaning \"AI will replace scientists\" remains a projection, not a current fact.\n\n- **The finding:** On multi-step reasoning tasks with genuine uncertainty, AI agents consistently fall short of human researchers. Not in every task. But the hard ones.\n- **The narrative check:** The AI research community has been publishing studies about AI replacing researchers while researchers publish studies proving otherwise. Ambiance.\n\n*We are apparently funding AI systems to replace scientists faster than AI can beat scientists at science.*\n\n**Sources:** [Nature](https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-026-01199-z)\n\n---\n\n## 💰 Venture Capital Had Its Best Quarter Ever. Half of It Went to AI.\n\nQ1 2026 set an all-time record with ~$300 billion in global venture funding, with AI startups accounting for so much that foundational AI startup funding in Q1 alone doubled the entire 2025 annual total.\n\n- **The numbers:** ~$297–300 billion raised globally in 12 weeks, led by infrastructure, orchestration, and applied AI.\n- **The trajectory:** Three consecutive record-breaking quarters. At this rate, \"AI bubble\" will need upgrading to \"AI atmosphere.\"\n\n*Investors are putting $300 billion per quarter into AI. The \"return on investment\" conversation will happen eventually. Apparently not yet.*\n\n**Sources:** [Crunchbase News](https://news.crunchbase.com/venture/record-breaking-funding-ai-global-q1-2026/)\n\n---\n\n## 🏃 China Is About to Run 300 Humanoid Robots Through a Half-Marathon\n\nBeijing's E-Town completed an overnight rehearsal for the world's first humanoid robot half-marathon — 300 robots from 26+ brands will run alongside actual humans on April 19.\n\n- **The logistics:** Full-scale rehearsal done. 300 robots. 26 manufacturers. The robots are navigating, balancing, and presumably not stopping at water stations.\n- **The meta-point:** China is simultaneously deploying humanoids in factories, selling them to consumers for $42,000, and entering them in road races. The \"physical AI\" strategy is not subtle.\n\n*300 robots in a half-marathon. The 12% success rate on household tasks will not come up at the finish line.*\n\n**Sources:** [CGTN](https://news.cgtn.com/news/2026-04-12/Beijing-completes-full-scale-test-for-humanoid-robot-half-marathon-1MhezccF19m/p.html)\n\n---\n\n## 🚗 Chinese Automaker Starts Selling Humanoid Robots for $42,000\n\nChery, the Chinese car company, began retail sales of its self-developed humanoid robot this week at approximately $42,000 — a consumer product, not an industrial unit.\n\n- **The market:** The humanoid sector attracted over $6 billion in investment in 2025. The robots are now available for purchase. At the price of a mid-range car. Which Chery also makes.\n- **The transition:** Physical AI went from research labs to factory floors to consumer retail in roughly 18 months. Whether anyone needs a $42,000 humanoid at home remains an open question.\n\n*A car company is selling you a humanoid robot for the price of a car. The product roadmap is coherent, at least.*\n\n**Sources:** [Robotics & Automation News](https://roboticsandautomationnews.com/2026/04/13/chinese-automaker-chery-begins-selling-humanoid-robot-to-consumers-for-42000-each/100544/)"
  }
]
